How to practise: a thread of practice tips I wish Iâ€™d worked out when I was younger ğŸ§µ

Being kind and patient with yourself is way WAY more effective and generates much more actual progress than beating yourself up. If you have no idea where to start with this, imagine how you might encourage a gifted but not very confident child

If youâ€™re SUPER struggling with a simple passage, thatâ€™s GREAT! Thatâ€™s your brain showing you what it needs to work on today. It will suck for the whole practice session, but just keep at it for a while. When you wake up the next day after sleeping on it itâ€™ll probably be fine

Are you a bowed string player? Do you think youâ€™re having a technical issue with your left hand? Really? Itâ€™s probably your right. Try changing the bowing, or just shifting mental focus to the bow.

Donâ€™t compare yourself to others in terms of how much time you spend practising. Everybody is different, everybody learns different things at different paces, and everybody works at a different intensity, there is no universal optimal amount.
There is no universally correct length of time for a single practice session. Some people are cool doing 3hrs in one chunk. I very rarely do more than 30mins at one time. Whatever works for you.

Try not to have performance anxiety in the practice room. Be HAPPY when you make mistakes - every mistake you make now, in this time youâ€™re taking for yourself, is an opportunity to fix it now before youâ€™re in a space where you *donâ€™t* want to be screwing up

Spending some of your practice time in front of a mirror to check your technique = good. Filming yourself occasionally = a better test because you wonâ€™t be correcting yourself by watching in real time

Jaw tension will screw you over good and proper. Iâ€™ve no idea how to fix this for wind/brass players but for strings/pianoâ€¦ try practising whilst pulling lots of faces, shaking your head around, chewing gum, anything to keep everything relaxed and mobile up there

Never be afraid of spending time on basics. Itâ€™s really easy to look at the bazillions of notes you have to learn and think you donâ€™t have time to work on open strings, or stabilising your intonation in 1st position. Always take the time, fundamental basics feed into everything

2. But these aren't normal times. As Covid activity slows â€” if that continues â€” could we see #flu activity pick up a bit? There are parts of the US where that's happening now. But I don't think there's enough flu circulating to have a big bump so late in the season. https://t.co/FsM2KAVbAp

4. @CDCgov doesn't count adult #flu deaths, they estimate them. The 2021-22 flu season burden estimates are that 2.4M people had flu, 23,000 were hospitalized & 1,400 have died.

Everyone is telling this poor tweeter, who has already published in McSweeney's etc to "read."

If one is already published in high quality venues, the trick is to create and cultivate second self inside yourself who reads what you write the way a stranger would. https://t.co/7O89VTwlR5

Workshops and groups, at their best, jumpstart this process by offering the writer a series of models for that second self.

This is one reason why emotionsâ€”positive and negativeâ€”run high in these settings.

Your second self won't know your reasoning for why you made this or that decision in a text, but will see your patterns, tricks, tendencies, and weaknesses. The idea isn't to "fix" these things, but to augment them, to be the only person in the world who writes your writing.

Your second self has an advantage over actual strangers in that it has read everything you've written and knows the shape and smell of those texts that only exist of flashes of images and subaudible tones. So, much better to the one who tells you what you're up to.

You can create this second self via journaling, via talking writing to a real-life friend who doesn't really listen (but the noetic infant in your BaiHui is!), reading author memoirs/biographies till you get sick of them like they're candy corn, and knowing that it is possible.
And now you know it is possible. So, carry on.

Elated to share our latest paper, "System-wide transcriptome damage and tissue identity loss in COVID-19 patients," led by @JIWOONPARK_ @jfoox in our lab & @RobSchwartzLab @RiceLaboratory @cemmeydan @RockefellerUniv @WCMCPathology @nygenome  https://t.co/ZZUNOJUHeR ğŸ§µ /1

We  used spatial protein and expression profiling on @nanostringtech GeoMx on 357 tissue sections from 16 patient lung samples and RNA-seq on 646 clinical NP swabs, plus  39 patient autopsies to define body-wide transcriptome changes in response to COVID-19. /2 https://t.co/a0cpya6u6L

SARS-CoV-was found across multiple tissues from deceased patients, including the lung, lymph node, kidney, liver, and heart, but mostly in the lung, and we even saw some evidence of intra-host variability of the virus /3 https://t.co/wyczyDwgGh
Each tissue showed its own disruption of normal transcriptional pathways, but the lymph node showed the greatest degree of change compared to controls. /4 https://t.co/Ir2FkqHeyL

The "creepiest" part was seeing how the normal cell type abundances of the tissues, like cardiomyocytes in the heart, were mostly lost, as if the cells "forgot" what kind of cell type they were supposed to be within each tissue, including the liver, lung & kidney: /5 https://t.co/JC7abjY54P

We also saw COVID-19-specific heterogeneity and spatial tropism in the lung, including genes related to regulatory T cell differentiation in alveolar tissues (PLK1, ATM) and IL6/JAK/STAT3 signaling in SARS-CoV-2-low vascular regions (SOCS1, CXCL11) /6 https://t.co/XFoPxZ1dDA

These data show that fibroblasts and many immune cells types were increased in most tissue types, while tissue-specific cell types, such as alveolar epithelial types 1 and 2 cells in the lung and cardiomyocytes in the heart, showed a decrease in COVID-19 relative to controls /8

Finally, since spatial data enables new kinds of cell-cell mapping and spatial analysis, we examined cell adjacency maps and saw that the spatial organization of cells in the lungs was especially disrupted in high viral load patients, distinct from flu or ARDS: /7 https://t.co/fCAVdbdpvM

It was a big team effort; thanks to the patients & their families who donated the tissues, @nyphospital staff, Alain Borczuk @ElementoLab @dcdanko @skimomiks @ShapiraLab @hajirasouliha @AfshinBeheshti @danjbuts @mjdmackay @nicktatonetti @LabMelnick plus all co-authors, thx! /fin

These high-resolution methods give us a unique view of the pathophysiology of COVID-19, and also these data can be browsed and downloaded here (thanks @cemmeydan): https://t.co/Fx9RjjQROB /9 https://t.co/z3qyy2DiuD

I ask because this feels like IV in reverse.

I am not interested in the effect of the loan on future biz performance. 

I am interested in the effect of the encouragement, "knowing you can get a loan,"  on future biz performance.

I have data on entrepreneurs who are randomly informed they have been approved for a biz loan. A minority of those approved eventually take the loan.

What is the best way to estimate the "informational/learning effect" of being approved vs. the effect of getting more capital?
If you were designing an experiment how might you estimate this? I think it's important that the approval is credible so I don't think you can randomize whether the firm gets the loan later on.
I have rich longitudinal data so can track shits in performance and uptake over time. Is there some way to use that?

This feels like a place where I should use mediation analysis, estimate how much of the effect runs through the capital vs. "other" channels... but that is going to require some rough assumptions in this context.

I don't think you can't just control for loan takeup because if "worse firms" take up loans once approved then the non-takers will by selection be better firms. The encouragement didn't impact their entrepreneur behavior, just caused worse firms to take loans.
Thoughts @RDMetcalfe @paulgp @PHuenermund @hyunjinvkim ?

@ProfAroraAshish @dani__messinese @arpitrage I described it as random to get at the causal inference question, in actuality its quasi-random with the probability of being notified you are approved increasing in quality.

@ProfAroraAshish @dani__messinese @arpitrage So we compare two firms of the same quality where one randomly knows they can get a loan in future vs.  the other does not.  

Knowing I can access future capital should change my current behavior, even if I don't use now, right?

In multivariable MR the first IV assumption becomes that the IV's must predict each exposure given all of the other exposures. So its not enough to look at the association between the SNPs and each exposure in your multivariable MR - you have to adjust for the other exposures

Our new paper on weak instruments in multivariable MR is now available online!  This is joint work with @WesSpiller and @jack_bowdenjack. 
Short thread below... https://t.co/p8OCsq8GEG
But what if F<10? well.... weak instrument bias isn't your only problem; heterogeneity tests will be too large and IVW estimation is no longer robust to balanced heterogeneity (/pleiotropy)
In this paper we develop a test for instrument strength in two-sample/summary-data analyses, this test can be compared to standard weak instrument critical values (translation: F>10 is good)

If your instruments are weak then IVW estimation results will be biased and imprecise. 
But....... because strength depends on all of the exposures the instruments can be weak even if all the SNPs are genome-wide significant for at least one exposure in the MVMR.
We have developed an R package ('MVMR') that can implement all of the statistics/estimators discussed available here: https://t.co/fwSIQ1s9B8

So we extend univariable weak instrument robust Q-statistics and weak instrument and heterogeneity robust MR estimation to the multivariable setting. Caveat; although the estimates are consistent when F<10 the weaker the IV's the less precise the estimates will be.

Thanks everyone for being patient, apologies for the initial launch tuning & we're committed to getting bounties into a good spot as fast as possible. Without all of your reports, it would have been difficult to find the root cause of some of the issues.

For 11.24, we've isolated the root cause of the rare case where winning teams sometimes continue to have an objective bounty active for them while actively winning the game and are working on a design fix.

Preparing a micropatch to address some concerns with Objective Bounties (hoping to hit later today): 
* Bounties kicking in on too light of a lead
* Bounties falling off too late when a team has clawed back a good chunk of lead

Objective Bounty micropatch is live: 
- Losing teams have to be more behind for Objective Bounties to activate
- Objective Bounties will fall off earlier when a losing team starts coming back

Investigating some edge cases where a team that's winning continues to have bounties

Two changes just micropatched out!
1. Damaging an objective bounty while it's deactivating will no longer reset the deactivation timer, as it was resulting in some situations where a team would rebound from moderately behind -> ahead if the team took multiple objectives in a row

2. Dragon & Soul values in determining which team has the lead have been reduced. This meant Objective Bounties could still be active when a winning team had Dragon Soul, then started losing, despite a massive lead for the newly winning team. This felt wrong and has been changed

I'm very excited to learn about things from the community (it's difficult to keep on top of it all!), so please reach out if there's things you can teach us. I'd love to hear them & learn!  

I'm excited to work & play with you all for 2022 and beyond :P

Elated to share our newest advance in #Volumetric #Bioprinting online @AdvSciNews https://t.co/18Nf3FDttM We print high densities of Liver Organoids into complex, large geometries, we counter light scattering andâ€¦Function Follows (the printed) Form @ERC_Research @pau_bernal1ğŸ§µğŸ‘‡ https://t.co/E7sZ24XSFz

(2/n) Back in 2019, we showed how visible #light #tomographic projections enabled printing cell-laden hydrogels into cm-scale constructs in a matter of few seconds. Bioengineering, photonics, tomographic algorithms and bioengineering at work together!
https://t.co/2etXVdDiIY

(3/n) The technique works very well with transparent materials. However, cells scatter light (and thanks to that, we have Flow Cytometry ğŸ¥³!). At high cell density, this can make printing more difficult, and eventually disrupt resolution and shape fidelity. How can we solve this? https://t.co/MVdV8YdrpE

(4/n) In extrusion printing we can tune hydrogel rheology, in light-based printing we tune optical properties! Inspired by https://t.co/SOxDO1y0Dk we studied a cell-friendly compound, iodixanol, to make our bioresin's refractive index match that of larger intracellular organelles https://t.co/CNNS2Ma3rJ

(5/n) In this way, prints resolve 40-50um fetures even with high cell densities (also in less than 20 seconds)! These are also printed in very soft gels (<2kPa) with human liver organoids. They are quite fragile, and in extrusion printing tend to be damaged by shear forces...

(6/n) ...but we don't use nozzles here! Organoids have better viability post-printing, larger size and mature better when differentiated, showing improved polarization, and can be assembled into any desired 3D geometry. Bonus: they seem to differentiate better than in Matrigel

(7/n) What about liver function? Printed into different triply periodic minimal surface lattices, the organoids are exposed to diverse media flow profiles when the prints are connected to a perfusion system. With the right architecture, key liver detox functions can be boosted https://t.co/DTU6lFG9pV

(8/n) You can read more about the bioprinting technology and the performance of these liver biofactories in the #OpenAccess paper, summarizing nearly 2 years of work. And don't forget to check the supplementary info (plenty of results there too!) https://t.co/STXhyx0wtT

This project investigated the 1/f spectral exponent of EEG spectra (roughly the steepness of the power decaye with increasing frequency). First, we validated the potency of EEG spectral exponents to track anesthesia-driven changes in E/I balance (Propofol vs. Ketamine). (2/12) https://t.co/EtnUmyc7Ab

The final version of our paper "Modality-specific tracking of attention and sensory statistics in the human electrophysiological spectral exponent" is out! A brief thread on the highlights (and supplements!) below. Paper: https://t.co/63JxLrHKjz
(1/12)

Next, we recorded EEG while participants focused on auditory or visual noise (simultaneous). Building on animal work and EEG spectral exps as a proxy of cortical E/I, we find that selective attention entails a topographically specific reduction of spectral exps. (3/12) https://t.co/CypIxi3mYY

Cog-neuro ephys tweeps now will of course wonder: â€œWhat about alpha power?â€ â€“ and with good right. We replicate common attention-related alpha power dynamics BUT these can be separated from 1/f effects using spectral parameterization and statistical controls. (4/12) https://t.co/TM2xK0ANWv

Neither alpha, low-freq power nor ERPs were able to account for attention-related diffs in EEG spectral exps. To us, this illustrates the unique power of such an approach and suggests the presence of two signatures that are often lumped together analytically & conceptually (5/12)

Such a tracking of 1/f sensory input offers an exciting addition to investigations of neural entrainment that focus on sinusoidal signals. Given plenty of 1/f signals in nature, their tracking might very well be relevant for successful behaviour (7/12).

Using the same dataset, we next tested for a link between the spectral exponents of sensory input and the EEG. Spectral exponents of stimuli and EEG aligned on the level of single trials and in a topographically-specific manner (6/12) https://t.co/buKkcSnq8S

Indeed, individuals who displayed stronger tracking of stimulus spectral exponents also performed better. While our sample size might not warrant strong inter-individual claims, the specificity of our results represents an exciting first step to be followed up on (8/12) https://t.co/wrVGa73PlB

Neural tracking can of course also be analyzed in the time domain instead of focusing on spectra. This can be achieved using multivariate temporal response functions (mTRFs). In brief, mTRFs estimate  time-resolved linear relationships between sensory signals and EEG data (9/12)
Data are here and code that reproduces all main findings can be found here: https://t.co/x5vfqU9OMO Feel free to get in touch with any questions (11/12)!

The supplements of our paper now contain the results of an entire mTRF analysis, including some interesting mismatch between modalities. Additionally, there are a bunch of other exhaustive control analyses in there that you might be interested in (10/12). https://t.co/OgEBrDthjP

Another great virtual conference, #FOCS2021, is on the way!  Before the time conferences got virtual, students from my university would rarely find the chance to participate in conferences, both because of the non-affordable costs and visa issues. 1/7 https://t.co/oeat0Tte2e

Online talks were not that popular, either. In spite of rich educational backgrounds (Sharif sends students to top graduate programs every year), students missed the chance to interact with their research communities and take advantage of attending conferences and talks. 2/7

However, the trend to organize online confs/talks/courses has mitigated the issue a lot. I have had the chance to take part in conferences (ICCV, NeurIPS), attend talks (e.g. TTIC & Harvard ML theory talks), and watch online courses (e.g. Harvard CS 229br) in the last months. 3/7

I am writing this to appreciate the community for these opportunities and let them know to what a great extent they have and could help groups underrepresented in social scientific events like conferences, by facilitating virtual attendance and publishing online materials. 4/7

Fees are another thing I could address. Although the virtual conferences have reduced the costs, it wouldn't be possible for me to attend ICCV without the registration code @vincesitzmann provided (thanks againğŸ™) or NeurIPS without the reduced fee. 5/7 https://t.co/sDzX9zJJhs

#FOCS2021 seems to be less attendance-friendly. Registration is required for workshops, financial supports are only available for US-based students, and there are no reduced fees like NeurIPS. Though, the mentoring lunches are open which is great! 7/7 https://t.co/vnPqvHVQ07

There are many valuable recorded materials available, but at least my experience was very different in attending the conferences and workshops, and I think it is not replaceable by watching and reading recorded materials. 6/7
